    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_354873143" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/354873143" />
    <a title="Inderjit Sanghera" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/900800-inderjit-sanghera"><img alt="Inderjit Sanghera" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1564826235p2/900800.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/354873143?book_show_action=true">Jun 24, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Inderjit Sanghera" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Inderjit Sanghera" href="/user/show/900800-inderjit-sanghera">Inderjit Sanghera</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer354873143" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9492710696942831597">One reviewer once quipped that Gormenghast reads like &quot;Dickens on crack&quot;- a statement which, perhaps, accurately describes the weird, wonderful and whimsical world of Gormenghast; from the cantankerous Flay to the Machiavellian Steerpike, to the lachrymose Lord Gormenghast and the eccentric Doctor Prunesquallor, the cast of characters who populate the novel only serve to accentuate the outlandish and grotesque, drug-addled atmosphere which pervades the novel.<br/><br/>Not only this, but the reader&apos;s sense</span>
  <span id="freeText9492710696942831597" style="display:none">One reviewer once quipped that Gormenghast reads like "Dickens on crack"- a statement which, perhaps, accurately describes the weird, wonderful and whimsical world of Gormenghast; from the cantankerous Flay to the Machiavellian Steerpike, to the lachrymose Lord Gormenghast and the eccentric Doctor Prunesquallor, the cast of characters who populate the novel only serve to accentuate the outlandish and grotesque, drug-addled atmosphere which pervades the novel.<br /><br />Not only this, but the reader's senses are worn out by a cacophony of images and colours; from the bilious sun-rise, to the dank and dreary forest, there is something nightmarish and decadent about the world in which Gormenghast is set. A world perpetually stuck in an endless cycle of pointless traditions and stifling conventions and whose peacefulness is ripped apart by the simultaneous rise of Steerpike and birth of Titus, which act as electric shocks jolting the world of Gormenghast from somnambulism. <br /><br />"“This tower, patched unevenly with black ivy, arose like a mutilated finger from among the fists of knuckled masonry and pointed blasphemously at heaven. At night the owls made of it an echoing throat; by day it stood voiceless and cast its long shadow."<br /><br />Although Gormenghast represents the pinnacle of fantasy, in the atmosphere Peake is able to create, in his grim ironic humour and wonderful use of language, in the uniqueness of his characters and the beautiful, poetic descriptions of nature, there is something fundamentally discombobulating about the novel; its very weirdness soon gets tiresome, the unreality of its characters begins to grate on the reader who soon tires the  megalomaniacal  twin-sisters, cantankerous servants and lugubrious lords and eventually begins to hark after something more grounded and human. A work of genius, but one best taken in bite-sizes. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9492710696942831597" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


